<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-449-624  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 449 624.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  May 14 1990 v36 n1809 p12(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A plan for strategic technologies - II. (technology and governmentstrategy) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Robertson, Jack.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The United States can retain its global strategic position in hightechnology by launching a national plan to gain leadership in highdefinition television (HDTV) systems.andP;  American companies alreadybuild the hardware necessary to create 'home centers,' which wouldinclude computing, image processing, and two-way visual trainingas well as entertainment facilities.andP;  Wiring cities with fiberoptics is the key to developing HDTV.andP;  'Wired city demonstrations'involving consortia of telephone, cable-television, and governmentinterests would create demand by ensuring an initial base of100,000 or more orders.andP;  Telephone companies are already layingfiber to homes.andP;  Innovative entrepreneurs must take risks in orderto commercialize home workstations, but the workstation marketlacks focus.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     High technologyHigh-Definition TelevisionForeign CompetitionStandardsGovernment RegulationFiber opticsUnited States.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>